# CSS Naming Convention Rules

## Overview
Follow these naming conventions to maintain consistency with the existing codebase structure and ensure meaningful, maintainable CSS classes.

## Core Naming Rules

### 1. Component Blocks
- Use kebab-case for multi-word components
- Examples: `.product-card`, `.header-content`, `.footer-navigation`
- Avoid: `.productCard`, `.product_card`

### 2. Component Elements
- Maintain existing BEM-like structure: `.component-name .element-name`
- Examples: `.product-card .title`, `.header-content .logo`
- Do NOT change to strict BEM format (e.g., `.product-card__title`)

### 3. Component Modifiers
- Use existing pattern: `.component-name.modifier-name`
- Examples: `.btn.primary`, `.badge.round`, `.product-card.featured`
- Do NOT change to double-dash format (e.g., `.product-card--featured`)

### 4. Utility Classes
- Use meaningful, descriptive names
- Examples: `.container`, `.grid`, `.flex`, `.text-center`
- Avoid Bootstrap-like meaningless classes: `.w-8`, `.h-12`, `.p-4`

### 5. Responsive Utilities
- FOLLOW EXISTING PATTERN ONLY - do not create new responsive prefixes
- Use only: `.small--`, `.medium-down--`, `.large--`
- Examples: `.small--hide`, `.medium-down--show`, `.large--text-center`
- Do NOT create: `.medium-custom--`, `.tablet--`, `.desktop--`

### 6. State Classes
- Use existing pattern: `.component-name.state`
- Examples: `.btn.active`, `.product-card.disabled`, `.field.error`
- Do NOT change to: `.component-name.is-state`

### 7. JavaScript Hooks
- Use `.js-` prefix for JavaScript-only classes
- Examples: `.js-modal-trigger`, `.js-accordion-panel`
- Do NOT mix styling with JavaScript hooks

## CSS Custom Properties

### Naming Convention
- Use kebab-case with component prefix
- Examples: `--product-card-image-height`, `--header-logo-width`
- Avoid: `--productCardHeight`, `--product_card_height`

### Usage
- Define in `:root` or component scope
- Use existing breakpoint variables from settings
- Follow existing pattern: `--scheme-background-color`

## Animation Names

### Naming Convention
- Use descriptive camelCase names
- Examples: `slideIn`, `fadeInUp`, `scaleHover`
- Avoid: `slide-in-from-top`, `fade-in-up`, `scale-hover`

## Media Query Organization

### Breakpoint Usage
- Use existing breakpoint variables from settings
- Examples: `{{settings.breakpoint_tablet}}`, `{{settings.breakpoint_mobile}}`
- Do NOT use hardcoded values like `768px`, `1024px`

### Responsive Class Structure
- Follow existing pattern: `.breakpoint--utility-name`
- Examples: `.small--hide`, `.medium-down--show`, `.large--text-center`

## File Structure

### Organization
- `assets/base.css.liquid` - Base styles, variables, resets
- `assets/component-name.css.liquid` - Component-specific styles
- `assets/utility-name.css.liquid` - Utility classes

### Component Files
- Group related styles together
- Use consistent naming for component files
- Follow existing file naming patterns

## Examples

### Good Examples
```css
.product-card { /* Component block */
  /* styles */
}
.product-card .title { /* Component element */
  /* styles */
}
.product-card.featured { /* Component modifier */
  /* styles */
}
.btn.primary { /* Button modifier */
  /* styles */
}
.small--hide { /* Existing responsive utility */
  /* styles */
}
```

### Avoid These Patterns
```css
.productCard { /* camelCase */
  /* styles */
}
.product_card { /* snake_case */
  /* styles */
}
.productCard__title { /* Strict BEM - don't change existing */
  /* styles */
}
.w-8 { /* Bootstrap-like meaningless classes */
  /* styles */
}
.medium-custom--hide { /* Creating new responsive prefixes */
  /* styles */
}
```

## Enforcement

### Code Reviews
- CSS naming conventions must be reviewed
- Maintain consistency with existing codebase
- Do not break existing responsive utility patterns

### Maintenance
- Update existing code to follow conventions
- Preserve existing BEM-like structure
- Use meaningful class names for new development

### Validation
- Follow existing breakpoint system
- Use settings variables for responsive design
- Maintain component-based organization